Ask HN: What do we do with all these shovels?
text:
I'm just a boring enterprise java dev most of the time, but over the last year or so have been amazed by what can be done offline with the new AI tools that are getting so much deserved attention. With only a shallow understanding of the concepts behind things like GPT/Dall-E/StableDiffusion/Whisper, I think many of us are justifiably overwhelmed and even anxious about the implications.

The world will catch on once a few killer apps establish better footholds, but we're not at all prepared for what's coming. ( omg doom and gloom :D )

It's as though we're in the middle of a gold rush, and most of us are using shovels. But a few new technologies just showed up, allowing tiny teams to create factories capable of generating bespoke solutions like self-guided/self-healing electric razor shovels, and quadruple edged camouflaged scanning bean shovel, etc..

Whichever shovel factories come out on top is somewhat irrelevant, though we'll probably some new billionaries in this area soon.

The thing I'm excited about most is that this will allow some 10x developer/creator types to become 10^x once they master the right combination of skills.

Ask HN: Personal Asset Management
text:
There was a recent thread that highlighted the difficulty people have in managing their digital assets to handover to a spouse or others in the event of their death. I think there's still a huge gaping hole when it comes to a product that manages all your personal assets. I was just curious to know if anyone knows of a product like that or if you have a process/collection of docs?

My asset management is basically all in my head. Not ideal but I never trusted password managers and I don't like the idea of writing everything down. I've just gotten to the point of doing it for general living expenses, bills and bank accounts but nothing else.

Ask HN: What happens when AI starts eating it's own dog food?
text:
I see more and more text extracts and AI generated images which are only sometimes loosely attributed to AI. Those results will surely become training data as time goes on. Any mistakes made will set AI into an endless loop of affirmation of its own mistakes.

Are we headed for a future where human knowledge and history is irretrievably corrupted by AI?

Is there a solution?
